note.p: This looks like Niall MacMhuirich's hand, using a different pen and ink (black instead of brown).

Confusingly, "dia" could mean either "for his [brother]" or "from his [brother]". While one might expect Partholon to be attempting to disrupt his brother's succession in his own favour, the fact that the passage goes on to state that his brother assumed the kingship with no apparent conflict with Parthalon suggests that Parthalon was acting on his brother's behalf.
This appears to be an erronerous repetition of "mac Simoin Bric". However, it is possible that a line is missing above, as the top margin is cut very closely on this page.

It is not clear whose brother. The lack of lenition suggests either Macha's or the three Cuans', who would then be sons of their own brother. However, bhuidhéin suggests someone already mentioned in the sentence ("his own brother"), who must be Dithorba. Lenition has thus been supplied on this basis.
